# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: policy-as-code
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:policy-as-code/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] "Governance" can also pertain to a specific sector of activities such as land, environment, health, internet, security, etc.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The degree of formality in governance depends on the internal rules of a given entity and its external interactions with similar entities.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] As such, governance may take many forms, driven by many different motivations and with many different results.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The most formal type of a governing body is a government, which has the responsibility and authority to make binding decisions for a specific geopolitical system (like a country) through established rules and guidelines.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] A government may operate as a democracy where citizens vote on who should govern towards the goal of public good.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Beyond governments, other entities can also have governing bodies.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These can be legal entities or organizations, such as corporations, companies or non-profit organizations governed by small boards of directors pursuing more specific aims.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] They can also be socio-political groups including hierarchical political structures, tribes, religious subgroups, or even families.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In the case of a state, governance expresses a growing awareness of the ways in which diffuse forms of power and authority can secure order even in the absence of state activity.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] A variety of external actors without decision-making power can influence this system of state governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These include lobbies, think-tanks, political parties, non-government organizations, community and media.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Governance is also shaped by external factors such as globalization, social movements or technological progress.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] From a normative perspective, good, effective and fair governance involves a well-organized system that fairly represents stakeholders' interests and needs.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Such governance guides the formulation, implementation, and evaluation of the group's objectives, policies, and programs, ensuring smooth operation in various contexts.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It fosters trust by promoting transparency, responsibility, and accountability, and employs mechanisms to resolve disputes and conflicts for greater harmony.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It adapts to changing circumstances, keeping the group responsive and resilient.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] By delivering on its promises and creating positive outcomes, it fosters legitimacy and acceptance of the governing body, leading to rule-compliance, shared responsibility, active cooperation, and ultimately, greater stability and long-term sustainability.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Many institutions of higher education - such as the Balsillie School of International Affairs, Munk School of Global Affairs, Sciences Po Paris, Graduate Institute Geneva, Hertie School, and the London School of Economics, among others - offer governance as an academic subjects.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Many social scientists prefer to use the term "governance" when discussing the process of governing, because it covers the whole range of institutions and involved relationships.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This considers the process by which governments are selected, monitored and replaced; the capacity of the government to effectively formulate and implement sound policies and the respect of citizens and the state of the institutions that govern economic and social interactions among them.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Like *government*, the word *governance* derives, ultimately, from the Greek verb *kubernaein* [*kubernáo*] (meaning *to steer*, the metaphorical sense first being attested in Plato).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Its occasional use in English to refer to the specific activity of ruling a country can be traced to early-modern England, when the phrase "governance of the realm" appears in works by William Tyndale and in royal correspondence from James V of Scotland to Henry VIII of England.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This usage of "governance" to refer to the arrangements of governing became orthodox including in Sidney Low's seminal text of the same title in 1904 and among some later British constitutional historians.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Since then, the term has gained increasing usage.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Governance can also define normative or practical agendas.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Normative concepts of fair governance or good governance are common among political, public sector, voluntary, and private sector organizations.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In its most abstract sense, governance is a theoretical concept referring to the actions and processes by which stable practices and organizations arise and persist.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These actions and processes may operate in formal and informal organizations of any size; and they may function for any purpose, good or evil, for profit or not.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Most theories of governance as process arose out of neoclassical economics.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These theories build deductive models, based on the assumptions of modern economics, to show how rational actors may come to establish and sustain formal organizations, including firms and states, and informal organizations, such as networks and practices for governing the commons.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Many of these theories draw on transaction cost economics.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] When discussing governance in particular organizations, the quality of governance within the organization is often compared to a standard of good governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In the case of a business or of a non-profit organization, for example, good governance relates to consistent management, cohesive policies, guidance, processes and decision-rights for a given area of responsibility, and proper oversight and accountability.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] "Good governance" implies that mechanisms function in a way that allows the executives (the "agents") to respect the rights and interests of the stakeholders (the "principals"), in a spirit of democracy.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Good governance is an indeterminate term used in international development literature to describe various normative accounts of how public institutions ought to conduct public affairs and manage public resources.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These normative accounts are often justified on the grounds that they are thought to be conducive to economic ends, such as the eradication of poverty and successful economic development.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Different organisations have defined governance and good governance differently.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The effectiveness of governments is not a straightforward and consentient type of governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Measurement and conceptualization of effectiveness is controversial and often used interchangeably with good governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] However, during the period of 1996–2018, an effort was made by the World Bank to create a comparable measure of the performance of governments; the Worldwide Governance Indicators (WGI).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The WGI is constituted by over 30 databases which are rescaled and categorized into six categories; among these is government effectiveness.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In short, effective governance is about quality of service, the independence of government and the quality of policies and implementation.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Adding to these components, one might argue that responsiveness to citizen's needs is high in an effective government.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Acting according to these needs, effectiveness is achieved by transparent, decentralized and neutral structures, that are consistent and disciplined.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Therefore, efficient financial management, high-quality and committed personnel and formalized and standardized ways of processes is needed.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] For the latter, governments became much more efficient with the arise of bureaucracies.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Nevertheless, governments in a rapidly changing environment need to be able to adapt quickly, so being bounded by rigid structures of functioning could work as a detriment.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The components of effective governance described above all have a domestic character, within the boundaries of the national territory, national policies and about the inhabitants of a country.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This is the internal aspect of effective governance, which mainly focuses on national services and policies.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The external aspect of effective governance on the other hand, exclusively focuses on the international domain of politics.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It entails the state's capacity to exercise its rights and fulfil its duties in alignment with international law, the representation of its people in the international political landscape and its participation in international relations.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The purpose of effective governance in the internal aspect is to be the sovereign within its national territory; in the external aspect to wield sovereignty over international relations.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] For this reason, it is a necessary characteristic of the state to have unrestricted capacity to act, without any form of dependence in both state and international law.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This independency is the core of statehood.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In an attempt to identify predictors of effective government, a study was conducted to investigate what characteristics of the state are more deeply established by effective governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The most striking conclusion was that effective governance has a big share in the economic growth and developing, although on the long term.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] However, this is a bi-directional relationship: economic growth does lead to more effective governance as well.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Moreover, effective governance does have a positive influence on reducing corruption, strengthening political stability, contribution to improved rule of law and improved government spending and accountability.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] As is the case with economic development, it is plausible the argue that effective governance and the named predictors are a positive feedback cycle: they reinforce each other, and so indirectly themselves.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] When a state fails to govern effectively, this does not simply imply the absence of the characteristics of effective governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] First of all, the absence of effective governance is lack of capacity of the state to supply its inhabitants with political goods, such as rights and freedoms.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Zartman describes how absence of effective governance comes about: "as the disintegration ofstate structure, authority (legitimate power), law, and political order".
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Five main characteristics are to be differentiated in the absence of effective governance: disorganizing of the structure of the processes in the state, violent conflicts, violations of human rights and social fragmentation, all of which have an endogenous character.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Since the early years of the 2000s (decade), efforts have been conducted in the research and international development community to assess and measure the quality of governance of countries all around the world.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Measuring governance is inherently a controversial and somewhat political exercise.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] A distinction is therefore made between external assessments, peer assessments and self-assessments.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Examples of external assessments are donor assessments or comparative indices produced by international non-governmental organizations.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] An example of a peer assessment is the African Peer Review Mechanism.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Examples of self-assessments are country-led assessments that can be led by government, civil society, researchers and/or other stakeholders at the national level.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] One of these efforts to create an internationally comparable measure of governance and an example of an external assessment is the Worldwide Governance Indicators project, developed by members of the World Bank and the World Bank Institute.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The project reports aggregate and individual indicators for more than 200 countries for six dimensions of governance: voice and accountability, political stability and lack of violence, government effectiveness, regulatory quality, rule of law, control of corruption.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] A Worldwide Governance Index (WGI) was developed in 2009 and is open for improvement through public participation.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The following domains, in the form of indicators and composite indexes, were selected to achieve the development of the WGI: Peace and Security, Rule of Law, Human Rights and Participation, Sustainable Development, and Human Development.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Additionally, in 2009 the Bertelsmann Foundation published the Sustainable Governance Indicators (SGI), which systematically measure the need for reform and the capacity for reform within the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) countries.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The project examines to what extent governments can identify, formulate and implement effective reforms that render a society well-equipped to meet future challenges, and ensure their future viability.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Section 10 of the Government Performance and Results Act (GPRA) Modernization Act requires U.S. federal agencies to publish their strategic and performance plans and reports in machine-readable format.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The International Budget Partnership (IBP) launched the Open Budget Initiative in 2006 with the release of the first Open Budget Survey (OBS).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The OBS is a comprehensive analysis and survey that evaluates whether central governments give the public access to budget documents and provide opportunities for public participation in the budget process.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] To measure the overall commitment to transparency, the IBP created Open Budget Index (OBI), which assigns a score to each country based on the results of the survey.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] While the OBS is released biannually, the IBP recently released a new OBS Tracker, which serves as an online tool for civil society, the media, and other actors to monitor in real time whether governments are releasing eight key budget documents.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The Open Budget Index data are used by the Open Government Partnership, development aid agencies, and increasingly investors in the private sector as key indicators of governance, particularly fiscal transparency and management of public funds.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Examples of country-led assessments include the Indonesian Democracy Index, monitoring of the Millennium Development Goal 9 on Human Rights and Democratic Governance in Mongolia and the Gross National Happiness Index in Bhutan.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Publishing performance reports openly on the Web in a standard, machine-readable format is good practice for all organizations whose plans and reports should be matters of public record.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] A collaborative governance framework uses a relationship management structure, joint performance and transformation management processes and an exit management plan as controlling mechanisms to encourage the organizations to make ethical, proactive changes for the mutual benefit of all the parties.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Environmental governance are the processes of decision-making involved in the control and management of the environment and natural resources.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These processes includes government, business and civil society.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Environmental governance may also refer to a concept in political ecology which promotes environmental policy that advocates for sustainable human activity (i.e. that governance should be based upon environmental principles).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Global governance (or world governance) comprises institutions that coordinate the behavior of transnational actors, facilitate cooperation, resolve disputes, and alleviate collective-action problems.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Global governance entails making, monitoring, and enforcing rules.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Within global governance, a variety of types of actors – not just states – exercise power.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In contrast to the traditional meaning of governance, the term *global governance* is used to denote the regulation of interdependent relations in the absence of an overarching political authority.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] An example of this is the international system, or relationships between independent states.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The concept of global governance began in the mid-19th century.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It became particularly prominent in the aftermath of World War I, and more so after the end of World War II.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Since World War II, the number of international organizations has also increased significantly.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The number of actors involved in governance relationships—such as states, non-governmental organizations, firms, and epistemic communities—has also increased significantly.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Various terms have been used for the dynamics of global governance, such as complex interdependence, international regimes, multilevel governance, global constitutionalism, and ordered anarchy.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Mainly it seeks to strengthen the health system, making sure that they are capable of meeting the health needs of targeted populations.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] More broadly, health governance requires a synergistic set of policies, many of which reside in sectors other than health as well as governors beyond the national governments, which must be supported by structures and mechanisms that enable collaboration.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] For instance, in the European context, a health policy framework called Health 2020 Archived 2020-04-27 at the Wayback Machine was developed as a result of the collaboration between State members in the region.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It gives policy-makers a vision, a strategic path and a set of priorities to improve health, guaranteeing that it is more equitable and sustainable.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In the 21st century, global trends (e.g., changing population demographics and epidemiology, widening social inequalities, and a context of financial uncertainty) have influenced health system priorities and subsequently the setting of the health governance function.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] These trends have resulted in the emergence of joint actions of all stakeholders to achieve seminal changes in 21st-century societies.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It is also important to consider that people have witnessed a global shift from traditional and reactive healthcare to proactive care, mainly enabled by investment in advanced technologies.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Recent artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine learning have made possible the automation as well as the standardisation of many processes in healthcare, which have also brought to light challenges to the existing governance structures.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] One of these challenges concerns the ownership of health data.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] "Metagovernance" is the "governing of governing".
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It represents the established ethical principles, or 'norms', that shape and steer the entire governing process.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] There are no clearly defined settings within which metagoverning takes place, or particular persons who are responsible for it.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] While some believe metagovernance to be the role of the state which is assumed to want to steer actors in a particular direction, it can "potentially be exercised by any resourceful actor" who wishes to influence the governing process.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Examples of this include the publishing of codes of conduct at the highest level of international government, and media focus on specific issues at the sociocultural level.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Despite their different sources, both seek to establish values in such a way that they become accepted 'norms'.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The fact that 'norms' can be established at any level and can then be used to shape the governance process as whole, means metagovernance is part of both the input and the output of the governing system.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Multi-level governance is the concept and study of the fact that many intertangled authority structures are present in a global political economy.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The theory of multi-level governance, developed mainly by Liesbet Hooghe and Gary Marks, arose from increasing European integration, particularly through the European Union.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Participatory governance focuses on deepening democratic engagement through the participation of citizens in the processes of governance with the state.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The theoretical framework of participatory governance as a variant of governing can be dated back to the early 1990s when academics began to stress the need for citizen participation in the government process.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This decentralization of state power "strength[ens] vertical accountability" improving the relationship between citizens and municipal governments.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The idea is that citizens should play a more direct roles in public decision-making or at least engage more deeply with political issues.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Government officials should also be responsive to this kind of engagement.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In practice, participatory governance can supplement the roles of citizens as voters or as watchdogs through more direct forms of involvement.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The role of citizens in participatory governance is to be afforded a form of state power as an elected group of non-political citizens to contribute to the public policy process.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Different manifestations of participatory governance include participatory budgeting, councils, and community organizations involved at the state level, taking on state studies or participating in social issues.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Over the last two decades, the most rapidly growing form of participatory governance has been participatory budgeting.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In 2004, the British Columbia Citizens Assembly was the first form of direct citizen engagement created to envision the provincial electoral system.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Action through participatory governance impacts policy at the municipal level.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] An example is the use of municipal housing councils in Brazil to impact policy adoption, which finds that housing councils are associated with a greater likelihood of program adoption beneficial to the needs reflected by the citizens.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The mechanism of participatory governance links the social sphere to the political to produce policies directly molded by or influenced by citizens.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Therefore, participatory governance potentially improves public service delivery and the allocation of resources.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] There is a distinction between the concepts of governance and politics.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Politics involves processes by which a group of people (perhaps with divergent opinions or interests) reach collective decisions generally regarded as binding on the group, and enforced as common policy.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Governance, on the other hand, conveys the administrative and process-oriented elements of governing rather than its antagonistic ones.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] This distinction assumes the possibility of the traditional separation between "politics" and "administration".
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Contemporary governance practice and theory sometimes questions this distinction, premising that both "governance" and "politics" involve aspects of power and accountability.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Regulatory governance reflects the emergence of decentered and mutually adaptive policy regimes which rests on regulation rather than service provision or taxing and spending.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The term captures the tendency of policy regimes to deal with complexity with delegated system of rules.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It is likely to appear in arenas and nations which are more complex, more global, more contested and more liberally democratic.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The term builds upon and extends the terms of the regulatory state on the one hand and governance on the other.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] While the term regulatory state marginalize non-state actors (NGOs and Business) in the domestic and global level, the term governance marginalizes regulation as a constitutive instrument of governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The term regulatory governance therefore allows us to understand governance beyond the state and governance via regulation.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Security sector governance (SSG) is a subpart concept or framework of security governance that focuses specifically on decisions about security and their implementation within the security sector of a single state.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] SSG applies the principles of good governance to the security sector in question.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Emerging thinking about contract governance is focusing on creating a governance structure in which the parties have a vested interest in managing what are often highly complex contractual arrangements in a more collaborative, aligned, flexible, and credible way.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Corporate governance refers to the mechanisms, processes, practices, and relations by which corporations are controlled and operated by their boards of directors, managers, shareholders, and stakeholders.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Corporate governance consists of the set of processes, customs, policies, laws and institutions affecting the way people direct, administer or control an organization.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Corporate governance also includes the relationships between people within an organization, (the stakeholders) and the corporate goals.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The principal players include the shareholders, management, and the board of directors.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Other stakeholders include employees, suppliers, customers, banks and other lenders, regulators, the environment and the community at large.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] IT governance primarily deals with connections between business focus and IT management.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The goal of clear governance is to assure that investment in IT generates business value and mitigates the risks that are associated with IT projects.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Land governance is concerned with issues of land ownership and tenure.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] It consists of the policies, processes and institutions by which decisions about the access to, use of and control over land are made, implemented and enforced; it is also about managing and reconciling competing claims on land.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] In developing countries, it is relevant as a tool to contribute to equitable and sustainable development, addressing the phenomenon that is known as 'land grabbing'.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The operational dimension of land governance is land administration.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Security of land tenure is considered to contribute to poverty reduction and food security, since it can enable farmers to fully participate in the economy.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Without recognized property rights, it is hard for small entrepreneurs, farmers included, to obtain credit or sell their business – hence the relevance of comprehensive land governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] There is constant feedback between land tenure problems and land governance.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] For instance, it has been argued that what is frequently called 'land grabbing', was partly made possible by the Washington Consensus-inspired liberalization of land markets in developing countries.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Many land acquisition deals were perceived to have negative consequences, and this in turn led to initiatives to improve land governance in developing countries.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The quality of land governance depends on its practical implementation, which is known as land administration: 'the way in which rules of land tenure are made operational'.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] And another factor is accountability: the degree to which citizens and stakeholder groups are consulted and can hold to account their authorities.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The main international policy initiative to improve land governance is known as the Voluntary Guidelines on the Responsible Governance of Tenure of Land, Fisheries and Forests in the Context of National Food Security (VGGT), endorsed by the Committee on World Food Security (CFS).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Landscape governance roughly refers to the rules, processes and institutions according to which decisions regarding the protection, management and planning of the landscape are made.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Landscape governance differs from country to country according to the national context (e.g., political system, organization of public administration, economy, culture etc.).
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The introduction of holistic approaches to landscape governance is the focus of the evolving interdisciplinary landscape research.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Such an approach is the conceptualization of landscape as a commons.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] For example, insurance companies exert a great societal impact, largely invisible and freely accepted, that is a private form of governance in society; in turn, reinsurers, as private companies, may exert similar private governance over their underlying carriers.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] The term "public policy" should not be exclusively associated with policy that is made by government.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Public policy may be created by either the private sector or the public sector.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] If one wishes to refer only to public policy that is made by government, the best term to use is "governmental policy", which eliminates the ambiguity regarding the agent of the policy making.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Project governance is the management framework within which project decisions are made and outcomes of a project are realized.
[src:policy-as-code/governance] Its role is to provide a repeatable and robust system through which an organization can manage its capital investments—project governance handles tasks such as outlining the relationships between all groups involved and describing the flow of information to all stakeholders.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:policy-as-code/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The Open Policy Agent (OPA, pronounced "oh-pa") is an open source, general-purpose policy engine that unifies policy enforcement across the stack.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA provides a high-level declarative language that lets you specify policy as code and simple APIs to offload policy decision-making from your software.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can use OPA to enforce policies in microservices, Kubernetes, CI/CD pipelines, API gateways, and more.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA is proud to be a graduated Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) project.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] This page covers core concepts in OPA's policy language (Rego) as well as how to download and run OPA.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA decouples policy decision-making from policy enforcement.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When your software needs to make policy decisions it **queries** OPA and supplies structured data (e.g., JSON) as input.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA accepts arbitrary structured data as input.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA generates policy decisions by evaluating the query input against policies and data.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA and Rego are domain-agnostic so you can describe almost any kind of invariant in your policies.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Policy decisions are not limited to simple yes/no or allow/deny answers.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Like query inputs, your policies can generate arbitrary structured data as output.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Servers communicate using protocols (such as `http`, `ssh`, etc.) over ports, which attach them to public or private networks.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The policy needs to be enforced when servers, networks, and ports are provisioned and the compliance team wants to periodically audit the system to find servers that violate the policy.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The following section explores how OPA can help implement this policy.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA policies are expressed in a high-level declarative language called Rego.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Rego (pronounced "ray-go") is purpose-built for expressing policies over complex hierarchical data structures.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] For detailed information on Rego see the Policy Language documentation.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If you edit the input data above containing servers, networks, and ports, the output will change below.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Similarly, if you edit the queries or rules in the examples below the output will change.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] As you read through this section, try changing the input, queries, and rules and observe the difference in output.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] They can also be run locally on your machine using the `opa eval` command, here are setup instructions.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] This section covers the building blocks of writing policies in Rego.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can see how these concepts come together to solve the network security policy in the Complete Example.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] To implement the security policy, the first step is to access and examine the infrastructure data.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When OPA evaluates policies, it binds data provided in the query to a global variable called `input`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can refer to specific parts of the input data using the `.` (dot) operator.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can use the same square bracket syntax if keys contain other than `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If you refer to a value that does not exist, OPA returns *undefined*.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Undefined means that OPA was not able to find any results.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The most simple policy decisions are made by writing expressions that perform logical operations on the input data.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] For example, to check if a server has a specific ID, use an equality check with `==`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA includes a set of built-in functions you can use to perform common operations like string manipulation, regular expression matching, arithmetic, aggregation, and more.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] For queries to produce results, all of the expressions in the query must be true or defined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If any of the expressions in the query are not true (or defined) the result is undefined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Expressions are joined together with AND only when they are in the same rule body.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] In this example, the checks against `input.servers` are OR'd since they are in different rule bodies.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] See Logical OR in the Rules section below for more detail.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can store values in intermediate variables using the `:=` (assignment) operator to help make more complex rules easier to read.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Variables can be referenced just like `input` and are, like `input`, immutable.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When OPA evaluates expressions, it finds values for the variables that make all of the expressions true.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If there are no variable assignments that make all of the expressions true, the result is undefined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Imagine you need to check if any networks are public.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] This approach is problematic, there may be too many networks to list statically, the number of networks may not be known in advance.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Like other declarative languages (e.g., SQL), iteration in Rego happens implicitly when you inject variables into expressions.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Now the query asks for values of `i` that make the overall expression true.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you substitute variables in references, OPA automatically finds variable assignments that satisfy all of the expressions in the query.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Just like intermediate variables, OPA returns the values of the variables.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can substitute as many variables as you want to do nested iteration.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If variables appear multiple times the assignments satisfy all of the expressions.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Just like references that refer to non-existent fields or expressions that fail to match, if OPA is unable to find any variable assignments that satisfy all of the expressions, the result is undefined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] While plain iteration is a fundamental building block, Rego also features ways to express *FOR SOME* and *FOR ALL* more explicitly.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] `some ... in ...` is used to iterate over the collection (its last argument), and will bind its variables (key, value position) to the collection items.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] It introduces new bindings to the evaluation of the rest of the rule body.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] For details on `some ... in ...`, see the documentation of the `in` operator.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Expanding on the examples above, `every` allows us to succinctly express that a condition holds for all elements of a domain.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Rego lets you encapsulate and re-use logic with rules.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Rules are just if-then logic statements.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Rules can either be "complete" or "partial".
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Complete rules are if-then statements that assign a single value to a variable.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Every rule consists of a head and a body.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] In Rego, the rule head is true *if* the rule body is true for some set of variable assignments.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] All values generated by rules can be queried via the global `data` variable from other packages loaded into OPA.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can query the value of any rule loaded into OPA by referring to it with an absolute path.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The path of a rule is always: `data.<package-path>.<rule-name>`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If you omit the `= <value>` part of the rule head the value defaults to `true`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] To define constants, omit the rule body.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you omit the rule body it defaults to `true`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Since the rule body is true, the rule head is always true/defined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If OPA cannot find variable assignments that satisfy the rule body, the rule is undefined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Partial rules are if-then statements that generate a set of values and assign that set to a variable.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] In the example below `public_network contains net.id` is the rule head and `some net in input.networks; net.public` is the rule body.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can query for the entire set of values just like any other value.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] In addition to partially defining sets, You can also partially define key/value pairs (aka objects).
[src:policy-as-code/latest] See Rules in the language guide for more information.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you join multiple expressions together in a query you are expressing logical AND.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] To express logical OR in Rego you define multiple rules with the same name.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Imagine you wanted to know if any servers expose protocols that give clients shell access.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The `default` keyword tells OPA to assign a value to the variable if all of the other rules with the same name are undefined.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you use logical OR with partial rules, each rule definition contributes to the set of values assigned to the variable.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] For example, the example above could be modified to generate a set of servers that expose `"telnet"` or `"ssh"`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Check out this blog post that goes into much more detail on this topic showing different methods to express OR in idiomatic Rego for different use cases.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The sections above explain the core concepts in Rego.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] At a high-level the policy needs to identify servers that violate some conditions.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] To implement this policy, define rules called `violation` that generate a set of servers that are in violation.
