[src:policy-as-code/latest] This section explains how you can query OPA directly and interact with it on your own machine.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] If you just want to quickly get a feel for the language without installing anything, check out the OPA Playground.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA binaries can be installed on macOS using Homebrew.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] This method supports both ARM64 and AMD64 architectures.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] It's also recommended to move the OPA binary into a directory in your `PATH` so you can run OPA commands in different directories.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] It's also recommended to move the OPA binary into a directory in your `PATH` so you can run OPA commands in any directory.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] These packages are maintained by their respective communities and may not always have the latest OPA version available.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can also download and run OPA via Docker.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The latest stable image tag is `openpolicyagent/opa:latest`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] See all available binaries on the GitHub releases.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Checksums for all binaries are available in the download path by appending `.sha256` to the binary filename.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The simplest way to interact with OPA is via the command-line using the `opa eval` sub-command.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] It can be used to evaluate arbitrary Rego expressions and policies.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] `opa eval` supports a large number of options for controlling evaluation.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA includes an interactive shell or REPL (Read-Eval-Print-Loop) accessible via the `opa run` sub-command.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can use the REPL to experiment with policies and prototype new ones.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you enter statements in the REPL, OPA evaluates them and prints the result.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Most REPLs let you define variables that you can reference later on.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] You can load policy and data files into the REPL by passing them on the command line.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] By default, JSON and YAML files are rooted under `data`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Prefixing file paths with a reference controls where file is loaded under `data`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] By convention, the REPL sets the `input` document that queries see by reading `data.repl.input` each time a statement is evaluated.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] See `help input` for details in the REPL.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] To integrate with OPA you can run it as a server and execute queries over HTTP.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] By default OPA listens for HTTP connections on `localhost:8181`.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] See `opa run --help` for a list of options to change the listening address, enable TLS, and more.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Inside of another terminal use `curl` (or a similar tool) to access OPA's HTTP API.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] By default `data.system.main` is used to serve policy queries without a path.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] When you execute queries without providing a path, you do not have to wrap the input.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] OPA can be embedded inside Go programs as a library.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The simplest way to embed OPA as a library is to import the `github.com/open-policy-agent/opa/rego` package.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The `rego.Rego` supports several options that let you customize evaluation.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] After constructing a new `rego.Rego` object you can call `PrepareForEval()` to obtain an executable query.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The prepared query object can be cached in-memory, shared across multiple goroutines, and invoked repeatedly with different inputs.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Call `Eval()` to execute the prepared query.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] The policy decision is contained in the results returned by the `Eval()` call.
[src:policy-as-code/latest] Don't forget to install the OPA (Rego) Plugin for your favorite IDE or Text Editor.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies intended to assist in objective decision-making are usually operational in nature and can be objectively tested, e.g. a password policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The term may apply to government, public sector organizations and groups, businesses and individuals.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Presidential executive orders, corporate privacy policies, and parliamentary rules of order are all examples of policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] While the law can compel or prohibit behaviors (e.g. a law requiring the payment of taxes on income), policy merely guides actions toward those that are most likely to achieve the desired outcome.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy or policy study may also refer to the process of making important organizational decisions, including the identification of different alternatives such as programs or spending priorities, and choosing among them on the basis of the impact they will have.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies can be understood as political, managerial, financial, and administrative mechanisms arranged to reach explicit goals.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] In public corporate finance, a critical accounting policy is a policy for a firm or company or an industry that is considered to have a notably high subjective element, and that has a material impact on the financial statements.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It has been argued that policies ought to be evidence-based.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] An individual or organization is justified in claiming that a specific policy is evidence-based if, and only if, three conditions are met.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] First, the individual or organization possesses comparative evidence about the effects of the specific policy in comparison to the effects of at least one alternative policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Second, the specific policy is supported by this evidence according to at least one of the individual's or organization's preferences in the given policy area.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Third, the individual or organization can provide a sound account for this support by explaining the evidence and preferences that lay the foundation for the claim.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies are dynamic; they are not just static lists of goals or laws.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy blueprints have to be implemented, often with unexpected results.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Social policies are what happens 'on the ground' when they are implemented, as well as what happens at the decision making or legislative stage.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The intended effects of a policy vary widely according to the organization and the context in which they are made.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy, as opposed to the more specific Public Policy, is the broad application of authority on a situation by any actor for goals intended by that actor.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] A way to extract the stated aims of a public policy is to analyze the goals embedded in the legislation or organization that establishes it.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] This approach helps clarify the explicit intentions behind a policy and provides a normative foundation for evaluating its effectiveness in practice.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] A meta-analysis of policy studies concluded that international treaties that aim to foster global cooperation have mostly failed to produce their intended effects in addressing global challenges, and sometimes may have led to unintended harmful or net negative effects.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The study suggests enforcement mechanisms are the "only modifiable treaty design choice" with the potential to improve the effectiveness.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The State of California provides an example of benefit-seeking policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] In recent years, the numbers of hybrid cars in California has increased dramatically, in part because of policy changes in Federal law that provided USD $1,500 in tax credits (since phased out) and enabled the use of high-occupancy vehicle lanes to drivers of hybrid vehicles.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] In this case, the organization (state or federal government) created an effect (increased ownership and use of hybrid vehicles) through policy (tax breaks, highway lanes).
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies frequently have side effects or unintended consequences.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Because the environments that policies seek to influence or manipulate are typically complex adaptive systems (e.g. governments, societies, large companies), making a policy change can have counterintuitive results.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] For example, a government may make a policy decision to raise taxes, in hopes of increasing overall tax revenue.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Depending on the size of the tax increase, this may have the overall effect of reducing tax revenue by causing capital flight or by creating a rate so high that citizens are deterred from earning the money that is taxed.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The policy formulation process theoretically includes an attempt to assess as many areas of potential policy impact as possible, to lessen the chances that a given policy will have unexpected or unintended consequences.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] In political science, the **policy cycle** is a tool commonly used for analyzing the development of a policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It can also be referred to as a "stages model" or "stages heuristic".
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It is thus a rule of thumb rather than the actual reality of how policy is created, but has been influential in how political scientists looked at policy in general.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It was developed as a theory from Harold Lasswell's work.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Later scholarship argues that stages models oversimplify policymaking, which is often iterative and shaped by multiple actors and shifting implementation contexts.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It is called the policy cycle as the final stage (evaluation) often leads back to the first stage (problem definition), thus restarting the cycle.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Harold Lasswell's popular model of the policy cycle divided the process into seven distinct stages, asking questions of both how and why public policies should be made.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] With the stages ranging from (1) intelligence, (2) promotion, (3) prescription, (4) invocation, (5) application, (6) termination and (7) appraisal, this process inherently attempts to combine policy implementation to formulated policy goals.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy formulation – Involves exploring a variation of options or alternative courses of action available for addressing the problem.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Decision-making – Government decides on an ultimate course of action, whether to perpetuate the policy status quo or alter it.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Implementation – The ultimate decision made earlier will be put into practice.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Evaluation – Assesses the effectiveness of a public policy in terms of its perceived intentions and results.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy actors attempt to determine whether the course of action is a success or failure by examining its impact and outcomes.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Anderson's version of the stages model is the most common and widely recognized out of the models.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] However, it could also be seen as flawed.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Sabatier, the model has "outlived its usefulness" and should be replaced.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The model's issues have led to a paradoxical situation in which current research and updated versions of the model continue to rely on the framework created by Anderson.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] But the very concept of the stages model has been discredited, which attacks the cycle's status as a heuristic.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Due to these problems, alternative and newer versions of the model have aimed to create a more comprehensive view of the policy cycle.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The Althaus, Bridgman & Davis model is heuristic and iterative.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] It is intentionally normative (a guide to what policymakers should do), and not intended as a diagnostic or predictive model (a tool for explaining or forecasting what will happen).
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy cycles are typically characterized as adopting a classical approach, and tend to describe processes from the perspective of policy decision makers.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Accordingly, some post-positivist academics challenge cyclical models as unresponsive and unrealistic, preferring systemic and more complex models.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] They consider a broader range of actors involved in the policy space that includes civil society organizations, the media, intellectuals, think tanks or policy research institutes, corporations, lobbyists, etc.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies are typically promulgated through official written documents.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy documents often come with the endorsement or signature of the executive powers within an organization to legitimize the policy and demonstrate that it is considered in force.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Such documents often have standard formats that are particular to the organization issuing the policy.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy types include those which are set by government, political parties and public organisations, and those which are adopted within businesses.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Political parties use policies to set out the basis on which they seek popular support at an election.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Within businesses, human resource policies and purchasing policies provide examples of how organizations attempt to comply with legal requirements and avoid negative effects.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Many large companies have policies stating that all purchases above a certain value must be performed through a purchasing process.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] By requiring this standard purchasing process through policy, the organization can limit waste and standardize the way purchasing is done.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The American political scientist Theodore J.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Lowi proposed four types of public policy, namely *distributive*, *redistributive*, *regulatory* and *constituent* in his article "Four Systems of Policy, Politics and Choice" and in "American Business, Public Policy, Case Studies and Political Theory".
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy addresses the intent of the organization, whether government, business, professional, or voluntary.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policy is intended to affect the "real" world, by guiding the decisions that are made.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Whether they are formally written or not, most organizations have identified policies.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies may be classified in many different ways.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The following is a sample of several different types of policies broken down by their effect on members of the organization.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Distributive policies involve government allocation of resources, services, or benefits to specific groups or individuals in society.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The primary characteristic of distributive policies is that they aim to provide goods or services to a targeted group without significantly reducing the availability or benefits for other groups.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] These policies are often designed to promote economic or social equity.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Examples include subsidies for farmers, social welfare programs, and funding for public education.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Regulatory policies aim to control or regulate the behavior and practices of individuals, organizations, or industries.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] These policies are intended to address issues related to public safety, consumer protection, and environmental conservation.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Regulatory policies involve government intervention in the form of laws, regulations, and oversight.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Examples include environmental regulations, labor laws, and safety standards for food and drugs.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Another example of a fairly successful public regulatory policy is that of a highway speed limit.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Constituent policies are less concerned with the allocation of resources or regulation of behavior, and more focused on representing the preferences and values of the public.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] These policies involve addressing public concerns and issues that may not have direct economic or regulatory implications.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] They often reflect the broader values and beliefs of the society.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Constituent policies can include symbolic gestures, such as resolutions recognizing historical events or designating official state symbols.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Constituent policies also deal with fiscal policy in some circumstances.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Redistributive policies involve the transfer of resources or benefits from one group to another, typically from the wealthy or privileged to the less advantaged.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] These policies seek to reduce economic or social inequality by taking from those with more and providing for those with less.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Progressive taxation, welfare programs, and financial assistance to low-income households are examples of redistributive policies.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Horizontal policy making and implementation involve joint work across governmental and departmental boundaries and across different social segments.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Its aim is to address broad social issues such as poverty and social integration.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] One example is Quebec's *Act to Combat Poverty and Social Exclusion* (2002), and its accompanying strategy and action plans.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] According to Gail Motsi's analysis of horizontal policy-making for the Institute on Governance, successful horizontal initiatives depend on effective consideration of *what needs to be shared* and *when it needs to be shared*.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] There is a continuum between information sharing, the sharing of objectives and the sharing of authority, with information sharing generally being easiest to establish, and the sharing of authority being the most difficult.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Broadly, considerations include political competition with other parties and social stability as well as national interests within the framework of global dynamics.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Policies or policy-elements can be designed and proposed by a multitude of actors or collaborating actor-networks in various ways.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Alternative options as well as organisations and decision-makers that would be responsible for enacting these policies – or explaining their rejection – can be identified.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] "Policy sequencing" is a concept that integrates mixes of existing or hypothetical policies and arranges them in a sequential order.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] The use of such frameworks may make complex polycentric governance for the achievement of goals such as climate change mitigation and stoppage of deforestation more easily achievable or more effective, fair, efficient, legitimate and rapidly implemented.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] In that sense, "reactive sequencing" refers to "the notion that early events in a sequence set in motion a chain of causally linked reactions and counter-reactions which trigger subsequent development".
[src:policy-as-code/policy] This is a concept separate to policy sequencing in that the latter may require actions from a multitude of parties at different stages for progress of the sequence, rather than an initial "shock", force-exertion or catalysis of chains of events.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Key components of policies include command-and-control measures, enabling measures, monitoring, incentives and disincentives.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Science-based policy, related to the more narrow concept of evidence-based policy, may have also become more important.
[src:policy-as-code/policy] Broadly, science–policy interfaces include both science in policy and science for policy.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:policy-as-code/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] In computer science, a **rule-based system** is a computer system in which domain-specific knowledge is represented in the form of rules and general-purpose reasoning is used to solve problems in the domain.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] The differences and relationships between these two kinds of rule-based system has been a major source of misunderstanding and confusion.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Both kinds of rule-based systems use either forward or backward chaining, in contrast with imperative programs, which execute commands listed sequentially.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] However, logic programming systems have a logical interpretation, whereas production systems do not.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] A classic example of a production rule-based system is the domain-specific expert system that uses rules to make deductions or choices.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] For example, an expert system might help a doctor choose the correct diagnosis based on a cluster of symptoms, or select tactical moves to play a game.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Rule-based systems can be used to perform lexical analysis to compile or interpret computer programs, or in natural language processing.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Rule-based programming attempts to derive execution instructions from a starting set of data and rules.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] This is a more indirect method than that employed by an imperative programming language, which lists execution steps sequentially.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Whereas the matching phase of the inference engine has a logical interpretation, the conflict resolution and action phases do not.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Instead, "their semantics is usually described as a series of applications of various state-changing operators, which often gets quite involved (depending on the choices made in deciding which ECA rules fire, when, and so forth), and they can hardly be regarded as declarative".
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] The logic programming family of computer systems includes the programming language Prolog, the database language Datalog and the knowledge representation and problem-solving language Answer Set Programming (ASP).
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] In the simplest case of Horn clauses (or "definite" clauses), which are a subset of first-order logic, all of the A, B1, ..., Bn are atomic formulae.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Although Horn clause logic programs are Turing complete, for many practical applications, it is useful to extend Horn clause programs by allowing negative conditions, implemented by negation as failure.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Such extended logic programs have the knowledge representation capabilities of a non-monotonic logic.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] The most obvious difference between the two kinds of systems is that production rules are typically written in the forward direction, *if A then B*, and logic programming rules are typically written in the backward direction, *B if A*.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] In the case of logic programming rules, this difference is superficial and purely syntactic.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] It does not affect the semantics of the rules.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Nor does it affect whether the rules are used to reason backwards, Prolog style, to reduce the goal *B* to the subgoals *A*, or whether they are used, Datalog style, to derive *B* from *A*.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] In the case of production rules, the forward direction of the syntax reflects the stimulus-response character of most production rules, with the stimulus *A* coming before the response *B*.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Moreover, even in cases when the response is simply to draw a conclusion *B* from an assumption *A*, as in modus ponens, the match-resolve-act cycle is restricted to reasoning forwards from *A* to *B*.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Reasoning backwards in a production system would require the use of an entirely different kind of inference engine.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] In his Introduction to Cognitive Science, Paul Thagard includes logic and rules as alternative approaches to modelling human thinking.
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] He does not consider logic programs in general, but he considers Prolog to be, not a rule-based system, but "a programming language that uses logic representations and deductive techniques" (page 40).
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] He argues that rules, which have the form *IF condition THEN action*, are "very similar" to logical conditionals, but they are simpler and have greater psychological plausibility (page 51).
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Among other differences between logic and rules, he argues that logic uses deduction, but rules use search (page 45) and can be used to reason either forward or backward (page 47).
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] Sentences in logic "have to be interpreted as *universally true*", but rules can be *defaults*, which admit exceptions (page 44).
[src:policy-as-code/rule-based-system] He does not observe that all of these features of rules apply to logic programming systems.
